There has been some work on a second set of root servers.
We have set up such a site here at NAS.

Recently discussion has been generated about moving 
them to 'the approved list'  of root servers.  I sort
of disagree with this philosophy.  We then have one 
large list of root servers, of which everyone tries
sri-nic.arpa first.  Perhaps a bit of engineering and
good administration is in order.  Similar to egp peers,
every site gets a set of root servers to use, that are
somehow somewhat more local to them.  The major 
problem with this is that the set of files to maintain
is even larger than the previous hosts.txt.  And, a
site is then dependent on connectivity and reliability
of some random root server.  

I guess it will continue to be more painful as long as
linear table searches stay around, and they will probably
stay around until many months go by without someone
piping up with a new and improved bug in named.  Here,
we use the name server for the mailers, but all interactive
programs still use a table search, because very few
people try to connect to sites outside the campus, and 
the table search is lots more reliable for those things
that are locally maintained.

					john

